summary: This is an FBI internal communication from the Criminal Investigative Crimes Against Children Unit (CACU) concurring with a travel request from Miami Division. It authorizes two Miami agents to travel to Sydney, Australia from March 14-21, 2011, to interview a United States citizen in connection with the Jeffrey Epstein and Ghislaine Maxwell child prostitution investigation. The document outlines required procedures for obtaining country clearance for official FBI travel overseas.

persons.name: Jeffrey Epstein
persons.context: Named in the document title and synopsis as a subject of the child prostitution investigation prompting the travel request.

persons.name: Ghislaine Maxwell
persons.context: Named in the document title and synopsis as a subject of the child prostitution investigation alongside Jeffrey Epstein.

events.title: FBI Agent Travel to Australia for Interview
events.description: Two FBI agents from Miami Division are authorized to travel to Sydney, Australia to interview a United States citizen as part of the Jeffrey Epstein and Ghislaine Maxwell child prostitution investigation.

keyFacts: The FBI's Crimes Against Children Unit (CACU) authorized international travel for agents to interview a U.S. citizen in Australia in March 2011 as part of the Epstein/Maxwell child prostitution investigation.
The travel authorization indicates the FBI's investigation into Epstein and Maxwell was active and involved international witness interviews as of 2011.

The document details the FBI's strict internal protocols for obtaining country clearance for official overseas travel, including coordination with Legal Attach√© (LEGAT) offices and the Department of State.
The purpose of the travel is described as sensitive, with instructions to avoid compromising details in unclassified communications like the electronic Country Clearance (eCC) request.
